.TH KSMBDCTL "8" "" "ksmbd-tools 4.2.12" "System Administration"
.SH NAME
ksmbdctl \- unified management tool for the ksmbd in-kernel SMB server
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B ksmbdctl
[\fIOPTIONS\fR] \fICOMMAND\fR [\fIARGS\fR]
.SH DESCRIPTION
\fBksmbdctl\fR is the unified management tool for \fBksmbd\fR, the in-kernel
CIFS/SMB3 server for Linux.
It replaces the individual \fBksmbd.addshare\fR, \fBksmbd.adduser\fR,
\fBksmbd.control\fR, and \fBksmbd.mountd\fR tools with a single command
using a subcommand-based interface.
.PP
\fBksmbdctl\fR manages user accounts, share configuration, server lifecycle,
debugging, and feature inspection.
It communicates with the \fBksmbd\fR kernel module via sysfs and Generic
Netlink, and manages configuration files
\fBksmbd.conf\fR(5) and \fBksmbdpwd.db\fR(5).
.SH ARCHITECTURE
\fBksmbd\fR uses a dual-space architecture that splits SMB processing between
the Linux kernel and a userspace daemon:
.SS "Kernel Module (ksmbd.ko)"
The kernel module handles all performance-critical operations:
.RS
.IP \(bu 3
\fBTransport\fR: TCP (port 445) and RDMA (SMB Direct) connection handling.
.IP \(bu 3
\fBProtocol\fR: SMB2/3 command parsing, response generation, and protocol
negotiation (SMB2.0 through SMB3.1.1).
.IP \(bu 3
\fBVFS\fR: File I/O operations via the Linux VFS layer, including
oplock/lease management for client-side caching.
.IP \(bu 3
\fBSecurity\fR: Message signing (HMAC-SHA256), transport encryption
(AES-128-CCM/GCM), and pre-authentication integrity (SHA-512).
.IP \(bu 3
\fBWork Queue\fR: Asynchronous request processing with credit-based
flow control.
.RE
.SS "Userspace Daemon (ksmbd.mountd)"
The daemon handles complex, policy-driven operations:
.RS
.IP \(bu 3
\fBAuthentication\fR: User credential verification against the password
database (\fBksmbdpwd.db\fR), NTLM/NTLMv2 challenge-response, and
Kerberos 5 via SPNEGO.
.IP \(bu 3
\fBShare Configuration\fR: Parsing \fBksmbd.conf\fR, applying share
parameters, and enforcing access policies.
.IP \(bu 3
\fBRPC Services\fR: DCE/RPC operations such as NetShareEnum (share listing),
NetServerGetInfo (server info), and WKSSVC (workstation services).
.IP \(bu 3
\fBSession Management\fR: User session lifecycle, tree connect/disconnect
handling, and connection tracking.
.RE
.SS "IPC Channel (Generic Netlink)"
The kernel module and daemon communicate over a Generic Netlink socket using
the family name \fBSMBD_GENL\fR (version 0x01).
.PP
The kernel sends request events to the daemon, which processes them and
sends back response events.
Event types include:
.TS
l l l.
Event	Direction	Purpose
_
HEARTBEAT_REQUEST	kernel\(->daemon	Liveness check
LOGIN_REQUEST	kernel\(->daemon	User authentication
LOGIN_REQUEST_EXT	kernel\(->daemon	Extended auth (Kerberos)
SHARE_CONFIG_REQUEST	kernel\(->daemon	Share parameter lookup
TREE_CONNECT_REQUEST	kernel\(->daemon	Share access check
TREE_DISCONNECT_REQUEST	kernel\(->daemon	Cleanup on disconnect
LOGOUT_REQUEST	kernel\(->daemon	Session cleanup
RPC_REQUEST	kernel\(->daemon	DCE/RPC call dispatch
SPNEGO_AUTHEN_REQUEST	kernel\(->daemon	SPNEGO/Kerberos auth
STARTING_UP	daemon\(->kernel	Startup configuration
SHUTTING_DOWN	daemon\(->kernel	Graceful shutdown
.TE
.PP
During startup, the daemon sends a \fBSTARTING_UP\fR event containing the
full server configuration (flags, protocol range, limits, interfaces,
netbios name, workgroup, etc.) as a
\fBksmbd_startup_request\fR structure.
The kernel module uses this to initialize its internal state.
.PP
The daemon's receive buffer is 1\ MB (\fBKSMBD_IPC_SO_RCVBUF_SIZE\fR),
and individual IPC messages may be up to 64\ KB
(\fBKSMBD_IPC_MAX_MESSAGE_SIZE\fR).
.SS "Data Flow"
A typical SMB request traverses the following path:
.PP
.nf
Client
  \(da
Transport Layer (TCP/RDMA)
  \(da
Protocol Processing (SMB2/3 command dispatch)
  \(da
\fI[if auth/share/RPC needed]\fR \(-> Netlink IPC \(-> ksmbd.mountd
  \(da
VFS Operations (file I/O via Linux VFS)
  \(da
Response Generation
  \(da
Client
.fi
.PP
Hot-path file I/O (read, write, lock, close) stays entirely in kernel
space for maximum throughput.
Only operations requiring policy decisions (authentication, share
config lookup, RPC calls) cross into userspace.
.SS "Worker Thread Pool"
The daemon processes IPC requests using a GLib thread pool.
The pool size is controlled by the \fBmax worker threads\fR parameter
in \fBksmbd.conf\fR(5) (default: 4, maximum: 64).
Each incoming kernel request is pushed to the pool and dispatched to an
available worker thread.
.PP
Worker threads handle:
login requests, share config lookups, tree connect/disconnect,
logout, RPC calls, SPNEGO authentication, and heartbeat responses.
.SH "GLOBAL OPTIONS"
These options may be given before any command.
.TP
\fB\-C\fR, \fB\-\-config\fR=\fI\,CONF\/\fR
Use \fI\,CONF\/\fR as configuration file instead of \fB/usr/local/etc/ksmbd/ksmbd.conf\fR.
.TP
\fB\-P\fR, \fB\-\-pwddb\fR=\fI\,PWDDB\/\fR
Use \fI\,PWDDB\/\fR as user database instead of \fB/usr/local/etc/ksmbd/ksmbdpwd.db\fR.
.TP
\fB\-v\fR, \fB\-\-verbose\fR
Be verbose. Enables debug-level logging to stderr or syslog.
.TP
\fB\-V\fR, \fB\-\-version\fR
Output version information and exit.
.TP
\fB\-h\fR, \fB\-\-help\fR
Display help and exit.
.SH COMMANDS
.SS "Server Lifecycle"
.TP
\fBksmbdctl start\fR [\fB\-p\fR \fI\,PORT\/\fR] [\fB\-n\fR[\fI\,WAY\/\fR]] [\fB\-j\fR]
Start the ksmbd daemon.
This is equivalent to running \fBksmbd.mountd\fR.
.RS
.PP
The startup sequence is:
.IP 1. 3
Parse command-line options and configuration files.
.IP 2. 3
Daemonize (unless \fB\-\-nodetach\fR is given): double-fork to detach from
the controlling terminal, become session leader, redirect stdio to
\fI/dev/null\fR, and switch to syslog logging.
.IP 3. 3
Write the PID to the lock file (\fB/usr/local/var/run/ksmbd.lock\fR).
.IP 4. 3
Initialize the Generic Netlink IPC channel (connect to family \fBSMBD_GENL\fR).
.IP 5. 3
Send the \fBSTARTING_UP\fR event to the kernel module with the full
server configuration.
.IP 6. 3
Enter the main event loop, processing IPC events from the kernel.
.PP
\fBOptions:\fR
.TP
\fB\-p\fR, \fB\-\-port\fR=\fI\,PORT\/\fR
Bind to \fI\,PORT\/\fR instead of TCP port \fB445\fR.
Overrides the \fBtcp port\fR setting in \fBksmbd.conf\fR(5).
.TP
\fB\-n\fR, \fB\-\-nodetach\fR[=\fI\,WAY\/\fR]
Do not detach process from foreground.
If \fI\,WAY\/\fR is \fB1\fR (or omitted), become process group leader
via \fBsetpgid\fR(2) but do not fork (default when flag is given).
If \fI\,WAY\/\fR is \fB0\fR, daemonize normally.
If \fI\,WAY\/\fR is greater than \fB1\fR, run entirely in the foreground
without any process group change.
.TP
\fB\-j\fR, \fB\-\-json\-log\fR
Output logs as JSON objects to stderr, one per line.
Format: \fB{"ts":\fR\fIepoch\fR\fB,"level":"\fR\fIlevel\fR\fB","msg":"\fR\fItext\fR\fB"}\fR.
Useful for log aggregation systems.
.RE
.TP
\fBksmbdctl stop\fR
Shut down both the ksmbd daemon and the kernel server.
Reads the daemon PID from \fB/usr/local/var/run/ksmbd.lock\fR, sends
\fBSIGTERM\fR to the daemon process, and writes \fB"hard"\fR to
\fB/sys/class/ksmbd\-control/kill_server\fR to terminate the kernel
server component.
Active client connections are forcefully closed.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl reload\fR
Notify the ksmbd daemon to reload its configuration.
Sends \fBSIGHUP\fR to the daemon process.
The daemon re-parses \fBksmbd.conf\fR and \fBksmbdpwd.db\fR.
.PP
.RS
\fBNote:\fR Share parameters and user database changes take effect
immediately after reload.
However, global parameters that are part of the kernel startup
configuration (protocol versions, signing mode, encryption mode,
feature flags, connection limits, I/O sizes) only take effect after a
full stop and start cycle, because they are sent to the kernel once
during the \fBSTARTING_UP\fR event.
.RE
.TP
\fBksmbdctl status\fR
Display server status information:
.RS
.IP \(bu 3
\fBModule loaded\fR: Whether \fB/sys/module/ksmbd\fR exists.
.IP \(bu 3
\fBModule version\fR: Read from \fB/sys/module/ksmbd/version\fR.
.IP \(bu 3
\fBDaemon PID\fR: Read from the lock file; verified alive with \fBkill\fR(2) signal 0.
.IP \(bu 3
\fBDebug components\fR: Current kernel debug state from \fB/sys/class/ksmbd\-control/debug\fR.
.RE
.TP
\fBksmbdctl features\fR
Display configured feature flags from \fBksmbd.conf\fR(5).
Loads the configuration file and prints a table of features and their
enabled/disabled state.
.RS
.PP
Features reported:
.TS
l l.
Feature	Config Key
_
SMB2 Leases	smb2 leases
SMB2 Encryption	smb3 encryption
SMB3 Multichannel	server multi channel support
Durable Handles	durable handles
Fruit Extensions	fruit extensions
Fruit Zero File ID	fruit zero file id
Fruit NFS ACEs	fruit nfs aces
Fruit Copyfile	fruit copyfile
.TE
.PP
Also shows: signing mode, protocol version range
(min/max), and worker thread count.
.RE
.TP
\fBksmbdctl version\fR
Output version information for both the userspace tools
(\fBksmbd-tools 4.2.12\fR) and
the loaded ksmbd kernel module (read from \fB/sys/module/ksmbd/version\fR).
.SS "User Management"
.PP
Users are stored in the \fBksmbdpwd.db\fR(5) password database.
After any change (add, delete, update), the daemon is automatically
notified to reload via \fBSIGHUP\fR.
.PP
\fBPassword storage:\fR
Passwords are converted to UTF-16LE, hashed with MD4,
and stored as Base64-encoded strings.
The database file format is one user per line:
\fIusername\fR\fB:\fR\fIbase64_hash\fR.
.PP
\fBUsername constraints:\fR
Must be valid UTF-8, between 1 and 47 bytes
(\fBKSMBD_REQ_MAX_ACCOUNT_NAME_SZ\fR = 48 including NUL),
and must not contain a colon.
Usernames are case-sensitive in the database.
.PP
\fBPassword constraints:\fR
Maximum 128 characters (\fBMAX_NT_PWD_LEN\fR - 1).
Must be valid UTF-8.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl user add\fR [\fB\-p\fR \fI\,PWD\/\fR] \fI\,USER\/\fR
Add \fI\,USER\/\fR to the user database.
If \fB\-p\fR is not given, the password is prompted interactively
(with confirmation prompt).
Fails if the user already exists.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl user set\fR [\fB\-p\fR \fI\,PWD\/\fR] \fI\,USER\/\fR
Add \fI\,USER\/\fR if missing, or update the password if it already exists.
This matches the legacy default behavior of \fBksmbd.adduser\fR
when neither \fB\-\-add\fR nor \fB\-\-update\fR was specified.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl user delete\fR \fI\,USER\/\fR
Delete \fI\,USER\/\fR from the user database.
The user is removed from the database file immediately.
Active sessions for the user are not terminated; they
expire according to normal session timeouts.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl user update\fR [\fB\-p\fR \fI\,PWD\/\fR] \fI\,USER\/\fR
Update the password for \fI\,USER\/\fR.
If \fB\-p\fR is not given, the password is prompted interactively.
Fails if the user does not exist.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl user list\fR
List all users in the user database, one per line.
Guest accounts (those matching the \fBguest account\fR parameter)
are excluded from the listing.
.SS "Share Management"
.PP
Shares are configured in \fBksmbd.conf\fR(5).
After any change (add, delete, update), the daemon is automatically
notified to reload via \fBSIGHUP\fR.
.PP
\fBShare name constraints:\fR
Must be valid UTF-8, between 1 and 63 bytes
(\fBKSMBD_REQ_MAX_SHARE_NAME\fR = 64 including NUL),
and is case-insensitive.
The names \fBglobal\fR and \fBipc$\fR are reserved.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl share add\fR [\fB\-o\fR \fI\,OPT\/\fR]... \fI\,SHARE\/\fR
Add \fI\,SHARE\/\fR to the configuration file.
Share parameters can be given with \fB\-o\fR (e.g., \fB\-o "path = /srv/share"\fR).
This option can be given multiple times.
If no \fB\-o\fR options are given, parameters are prompted interactively;
for each parameter, the current value (or default) is shown and can be
accepted by pressing Enter, or replaced by typing a new value.
Fails if the share already exists.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl share set\fR [\fB\-o\fR \fI\,OPT\/\fR]... \fI\,SHARE\/\fR
Add \fI\,SHARE\/\fR if missing, or update it if it already exists.
This matches the legacy default behavior of \fBksmbd.addshare\fR
when neither \fB\-\-add\fR nor \fB\-\-update\fR was specified.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl share delete\fR \fI\,SHARE\/\fR
Delete \fI\,SHARE\/\fR from the configuration file.
When deleting the \fBglobal\fR section, its parameters are reset to
defaults rather than removed.
Active connections to the share are not terminated.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl share update\fR [\fB\-o\fR \fI\,OPT\/\fR]... \fI\,SHARE\/\fR
Update parameters for \fI\,SHARE\/\fR in the configuration file.
Only the specified parameters are changed; unmentioned parameters
retain their current values.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl share list\fR [\fB\-\-live\fR]
Without \fB\-\-live\fR, list share names from \fBksmbd.conf\fR.
With \fB\-\-live\fR, query the running daemon over FIFO/\fBSIGUSR1\fR
and list active share configuration from userspace daemon state.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl share show\fR \fI\,SHARE\/\fR
Show all configuration parameters for \fI\,SHARE\/\fR, including defaults
for parameters not explicitly set.
.SS "Debug Controls"
.PP
Debug components control kernel-level debug printing via
\fB/sys/class/ksmbd\-control/debug\fR.
Requires the ksmbd module to be loaded.
Debug output appears in the kernel log, accessible via \fBdmesg\fR(1)
or \fBjournalctl \-k\fR.
.PP
Available debug components and the subsystems they cover:
.TS
l l.
Component	Covers
_
\fBsmb\fR	SMB protocol parsing, command dispatch, negotiation
\fBauth\fR	Authentication, NTLM challenges, Kerberos/SPNEGO
\fBvfs\fR	VFS operations (open, read, write, close, stat)
\fBoplock\fR	Oplock/lease grants, breaks, and state transitions
\fBipc\fR	Kernel-userspace netlink IPC messages
\fBconn\fR	Connection lifecycle (accept, close, timeout)
\fBrdma\fR	SMB Direct / RDMA transport operations
\fBall\fR	All of the above simultaneously
.TE
.PP
Components are toggled: enabling an already-enabled component disables it.
Enabled components are shown enclosed in brackets (\fB[]\fR) in the debug
output.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl debug set\fR \fI\,COMPONENT\/\fR
Toggle debug printing for \fI\,COMPONENT\/\fR.
After toggling, the current state of all components is displayed.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl debug show\fR
Display currently enabled debug components without changing anything.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl debug off\fR
Disable all debug output.
.SS "Configuration"
.TP
\fBksmbdctl config show\fR [\fI\,SECTION\/\fR]
Display the current configuration.
Without \fI\,SECTION\/\fR, shows all sections (global and all shares).
With \fI\,SECTION\/\fR, shows only that section
(e.g., \fBksmbdctl config show global\fR).
Parameters are shown in \fIkey\fR \fB=\fR \fIvalue\fR format.
.TP
\fBksmbdctl config validate\fR
Parse and validate the configuration file and user database
without starting the daemon.
Checks for syntax errors, invalid parameter names, unknown
sections, and reference integrity (e.g., users in \fBvalid users\fR
existing in the password database).
Reports errors on stderr and exits with status 0 if valid,
or 1 if errors were found.
.SH "AUTHENTICATION"
\fBksmbd\fR supports multiple authentication mechanisms, negotiated during
the SMB session setup phase.
.SS "NTLM / NTLMv2"
The default authentication method.
The client sends an authentication request; the kernel module
forwards it to the daemon via the \fBLOGIN_REQUEST\fR netlink event.
The daemon looks up the user in \fBksmbdpwd.db\fR, computes the
expected NTLM response, and returns either \fBKSMBD_USER_FLAG_OK\fR
or \fBKSMBD_USER_FLAG_BAD_PASSWORD\fR in the \fBLOGIN_RESPONSE\fR.
.PP
Password hashes are stored as MD4(UTF-16LE(password)),
Base64-encoded.
The hash is 16 bytes (128 bits); the maximum hash field in
the netlink message is 18 bytes (\fBKSMBD_REQ_MAX_HASH_SZ\fR).
.SS "Kerberos 5 / SPNEGO"
When \fBkerberos support = yes\fR is set in \fBksmbd.conf\fR(5):
.IP 1. 3
The server advertises Kerberos as a supported mechanism during
SPNEGO negotiation.
.IP 2. 3
The client sends a Kerberos AP-REQ ticket.
.IP 3. 3
The kernel forwards it to the daemon via \fBSPNEGO_AUTHEN_REQUEST\fR.
.IP 4. 3
The daemon validates the ticket against the keytab file
(configured via \fBkerberos keytab file\fR, default:
\fB/etc/krb5.keytab\fR) using the service principal
(configured via \fBkerberos service name\fR, default:
\fBcifs/\fR\fIFQDN\fR).
.IP 5. 3
The result is sent back via \fBSPNEGO_AUTHEN_RESPONSE\fR.
.PP
Kerberos requires the daemon to be built with Kerberos 5 library support.
.SS "Guest Access"
Guest (anonymous) access is controlled by three parameters:
.IP \(bu 3
\fBguest ok\fR (per-share): Allow passwordless connections.
.IP \(bu 3
\fBguest account\fR (global/per-share): System user for guest sessions.
.IP \(bu 3
\fBmap to guest\fR (global): When to auto-map failed logins to guest.
Set to \fBbad user\fR to map unknown usernames to guest automatically.
.PP
Guest connections run under the UID/GID of the system user specified by
\fBguest account\fR (default: \fBnobody\fR).
The \fBrestrict anonymous\fR parameter (0, 1, or 2) further restricts what
anonymous connections can access.
.SH "SECURITY MODEL"
.SS "Message Signing"
SMB2/3 message signing protects against man-in-the-middle attacks by
computing an HMAC-SHA256 over each message.
.PP
Controlled by \fBserver signing\fR in \fBksmbd.conf\fR(5):
.TS
l l.
Value	Behavior
_
\fBdisabled\fR	Never sign (fastest, least secure)
\fBauto\fR	Sign if the client requests (default)
\fBmandatory\fR	Require signing; reject unsigned clients
.TE
.PP
Signing adds approximately 5\(en10% CPU overhead per message.
For security-sensitive environments, use \fBmandatory\fR.
.SS "Transport Encryption"
SMB3 transport encryption (AES-128-CCM or AES-256-GCM, depending on
protocol version) encrypts the entire SMB message payload.
Requires SMB 3.0 or higher.
.PP
Controlled by \fBsmb3 encryption\fR in \fBksmbd.conf\fR(5):
.TS
l l.
Value	Behavior
_
\fBdisabled\fR	Never encrypt; refuse encryption requests
\fBauto\fR	Encrypt if the client requests (default)
\fBmandatory\fR	Require encryption; SMB 2.x clients cannot connect
.TE
.PP
Encryption is stronger than signing and makes signing redundant
(encrypted messages include an authentication tag).
.SS "Pre-Authentication Integrity (SMB 3.1.1)"
SMB 3.1.1 clients and servers maintain a running SHA-512 hash of
all negotiation messages before authentication completes.
This prevents downgrade attacks and ensures both sides agreed on
the same negotiation parameters.
This is automatic and cannot be disabled for SMB 3.1.1 connections.
.SS "Access Control"
Access to shares is controlled at multiple layers:
.IP 1. 3
\fBAuthentication\fR: User must be in \fBksmbdpwd.db\fR (or
guest access allowed).
.IP 2. 3
\fBUser ACL\fR: \fBvalid users\fR / \fBinvalid users\fR determine
who can connect.
\fBinvalid users\fR takes precedence.
.IP 3. 3
\fBHost ACL\fR: \fBhosts allow\fR / \fBhosts deny\fR restrict by
source IP/CIDR.
\fBhosts deny\fR takes precedence.
When both are empty, all hosts are allowed.
.IP 4. 3
\fBPermission Level\fR: \fBread only\fR / \fBread list\fR /
\fBwrite list\fR determine read/write access.
Precedence: \fBread list\fR > \fBwrite list\fR > \fBread only\fR.
.IP 5. 3
\fBFilesystem Permissions\fR: Linux UID/GID/mode bits and optional
ACL xattrs are enforced by the kernel.
.PP
The user identity used for filesystem operations is determined by:
.RS
.IP \(bu 3
The authenticated user's UID/GID (looked up via \fBgetpwnam\fR(3)).
.IP \(bu 3
Override with \fBforce user\fR and/or \fBforce group\fR (per-share).
.IP \(bu 3
New file permissions: (\fIrequested\fR AND \fBcreate mask\fR) OR
\fBforce create mode\fR.
.IP \(bu 3
New directory permissions: (\fIrequested\fR AND \fBdirectory mask\fR) OR
\fBforce directory mode\fR.
.RE
.SH "PROTOCOL NEGOTIATION"
\fBksmbd\fR supports SMB protocol versions from SMB1 through SMB3.1.1.
The protocol version is negotiated during the initial connection:
.TS
l l l.
Version	Identifier	Key Features
_
SMB1	SMB1	Legacy; insecure; avoid
SMB2.0	SMB2_20	Large MTU, compounding
SMB2.1	SMB2_10	Leases, multi-credit
SMB3.0	SMB3_00	Encryption, multichannel, SMB Direct
SMB3.0.2	SMB3_02	Lease V2
SMB3.1.1	SMB3_11	Pre-auth integrity, posix extensions
.TE
.PP
The server negotiates the highest version both sides support, bounded by
\fBserver min protocol\fR and \fBserver max protocol\fR.
For best security and performance, set \fBserver min protocol = SMB2_10\fR
(or higher) to disable SMB1.
.SH "PERFORMANCE TUNING"
.SS "I/O Size Parameters"
.TS
l l l.
Parameter	Default	Effect
_
smb2 max read	4 MiB	Max read payload per request
smb2 max write	4 MiB	Max write payload per request
smb2 max trans	1 MiB	Max transactional buffer
smbd max io size	8 MiB	Max RDMA read/write size
.TE
.PP
Larger values improve throughput for sequential workloads but increase
per-request kernel memory usage.
For high-throughput file serving, increasing to 8\(en16\ MiB can help.
For memory-constrained systems, keep defaults.
.SS "Credit Control"
\fBsmb2 max credits\fR (default: 8192) controls how many operations a single
client can have in flight simultaneously.
Higher values improve throughput for highly parallel workloads
(e.g., multi-threaded copy, database access) but allow a single client to
consume more server resources.
.SS "Connection Limits"
.TS
l l l.
Parameter	Default	Scope
_
max connections (global)	256	Total server-wide connections
max connections (share)	128	Per-share connections
max ip connections	32	Per-IP address connections
max active sessions	1024	Total authenticated sessions
max open files	10000	Open file handles per client
.TE
.PP
\fBmax ip connections\fR provides basic protection against connection floods
from a single source.
A value of 0 for any connection limit sets it to the maximum (65536).
.SS "Leases and Oplocks"
\fBsmb2 leases = yes\fR enables directory leases, which allow clients to
cache file and directory metadata locally.
This dramatically reduces network round-trips for applications that
repeatedly access the same files (e.g., build systems, IDEs).
.PP
\fBoplocks = yes\fR (per-share) enables opportunistic locks, which allow
clients to cache file data and batch writes.
Both should be enabled unless you need immediate cross-client visibility
of file changes.
.SS "Worker Threads"
\fBmax worker threads\fR (default: 4, max: 64) controls the daemon's IPC
processing capacity.
Increase this if authentication latency is high (e.g., LDAP/AD-backed
Kerberos) or if many clients connect simultaneously.
For most deployments, the default of 4 is sufficient.
.SS "Multichannel"
\fBserver multi channel support = yes\fR enables SMB3 multichannel, which
allows clients to aggregate bandwidth across multiple network interfaces.
Requires SMB 3.0+, multiple NICs on both client and server, and proper
network configuration.
Provides automatic failover if one path goes down.
.SS "Durable Handles"
\fBdurable handles = yes\fR allows clients to reconnect to open files after
brief network interruptions without losing state.
The server preserves file handles during the grace period.
Useful for Wi-Fi clients, VPN connections, and continuous availability
scenarios.
.SH "MACOS INTEGRATION"
\fBksmbd\fR includes extensive macOS compatibility via the AAPL SMB2
protocol extension (commonly called "Fruit", after Samba's
\fBvfs_fruit\fR module).
.SS "AAPL Negotiation"
When \fBfruit extensions = yes\fR (default), the server responds to
Apple's AAPL create context during \fBSMB2 CREATE\fR with negotiated
capabilities.
This enables:
.IP \(bu 3
Enriched directory listings (Finder metadata, permissions, resource forks
in a single round-trip).
.IP \(bu 3
Server model icon in Finder sidebar (controlled by \fBfruit model\fR).
.IP \(bu 3
Zero file IDs to prevent CNID mismatch issues (\fBfruit zero file id\fR).
.IP \(bu 3
Server-side copy via COPY_CHUNK_WRITE (\fBfruit copyfile\fR).
.IP \(bu 3
Synthetic NFS ACEs for Unix permission mapping (\fBfruit nfs aces\fR).
.PP
These extensions have no effect on non-Apple clients.
.SS "Time Machine"
To set up a Time Machine backup share:
.IP 1. 3
Create the share directory and set permissions.
.IP 2. 3
Configure the share with \fBfruit time machine = yes\fR.
.IP 3. 3
Optionally set \fBfruit time machine max size\fR to limit disk usage.
.IP 4. 3
Ensure \fBfruit extensions = yes\fR in \fB[global]\fR.
.IP 5. 3
Optionally enable \fBdurable handles = yes\fR for backup reliability.
.IP 6. 3
Configure mDNS advertising (see \fBmDNS INTEGRATION\fR below).
.PP
Each Time Machine share is advertised with a unique per-share UUID
in the \fB_adisk._tcp\fR mDNS TXT record (\fBadVU=\fR field),
derived deterministically from the server UUID and share name.
This allows macOS to reliably identify backup volumes across reboots.
.SS "Recommended VFS Modules"
For macOS shares, add the following VFS modules:
.PP
.nf
vfs objects = acl_xattr streams_xattr
.fi
.PP
\fBacl_xattr\fR stores Windows-style ACLs as extended attributes.
\fBstreams_xattr\fR stores NTFS alternate data streams (including
macOS resource forks and Finder info) as xattrs.
.SH "MDNS INTEGRATION"
The optional \fBksmbd-mdns-configure\fR script generates mDNS service
files from \fBksmbd.conf\fR so that the SMB server is automatically
discoverable on the local network.
.PP
Supported mDNS backends:
.TS
l l.
Backend	Configuration Files
_
\fBavahi\fR	/etc/avahi/services/ksmbd-*.service
\fBresolved\fR	/etc/systemd/dnssd/ksmbd-*.dnssd
\fBmdnsd\fR	/etc/mdns.d/ksmbd-*.service
\fBmdnsresponder\fR	/usr/local/lib/ksmbd/ksmbd-mdns-register
.TE
.PP
Services advertised:
.IP \(bu 3
\fB_smb._tcp\fR on the configured port (always).
.IP \(bu 3
\fB_adisk._tcp\fR on port 9 with per-volume TXT records (when Time Machine
shares are configured).
.PP
Configuration is idempotent: the script caches a hash of the current
configuration and skips regeneration if nothing has changed.
.PP
\fBksmbd.conf\fR(5) provides two optional parameters to control mDNS:
.TP
\fBmdns bonjour\fR (yes | no | auto)
Master switch for mDNS advertising.
\fByes\fR enables and fails if no backend is found.
\fBno\fR disables entirely.
\fBauto\fR (default) enables if a backend is available.
.TP
\fBmdns backend\fR (auto | avahi | resolved | mdnsd | mdnsresponder)
Force a specific mDNS backend.
\fBauto\fR (default) detects the best available.
.SH "DEBUGGING AND TROUBLESHOOTING"
.SS "Kernel Debug Output"
Enable kernel debug components to diagnose protocol issues:
.PP
.nf
# Enable SMB protocol tracing:
ksmbdctl debug set smb

# Enable authentication tracing:
ksmbdctl debug set auth

# Enable everything:
ksmbdctl debug set all

# View output:
dmesg \-wH
# or: journalctl \-kf

# Disable all:
ksmbdctl debug off
.fi
.PP
Debug output is verbose.
Enable only the components you need, and disable them when done.
.SS "Daemon Logging"
The daemon logs to syslog by default (facility: daemon).
For interactive debugging, start in foreground mode:
.PP
.nf
ksmbdctl start \-\-nodetach \-\-verbose
.fi
.PP
For structured log ingestion:
.PP
.nf
ksmbdctl start \-\-nodetach \-\-json\-log
.fi
.SS "Configuration Validation"
Validate configuration without starting the daemon:
.PP
.nf
ksmbdctl config validate
.fi
.PP
This catches syntax errors, invalid parameter values, and
cross-reference issues before a restart.
.SS "Common Problems"
.TP
\fBModule not loaded\fR
Run \fBmodprobe ksmbd\fR to load the kernel module.
Check \fBdmesg\fR for load errors.
Verify with \fBksmbdctl status\fR.
.TP
\fBDaemon not starting (port in use)\fR
Port 445 may be in use by Samba (\fBsmbd\fR).
Stop Samba first: \fBsystemctl stop smbd\fR.
Or use a different port: \fBksmbdctl start \-p 4455\fR.
.TP
\fBAuthentication failures\fR
Verify the user exists: \fBksmbdctl user list\fR.
Check password: delete and re-add the user.
Enable auth debug: \fBksmbdctl debug set auth\fR.
.TP
\fBPermission denied on share\fR
Check \fBvalid users\fR, \fBinvalid users\fR, \fBhosts allow\fR,
\fBhosts deny\fR, and \fBread only\fR settings.
Verify filesystem permissions on the share path.
Check \fBforce user\fR / \fBforce group\fR mapping.
.TP
\fBmacOS cannot find server\fR
Verify mDNS is configured: run \fBksmbd-mdns-configure\fR.
Check Avahi/systemd-resolved is running.
Test with: \fBdns-sd \-B _smb._tcp\fR or \fBavahi-browse \-rt _smb._tcp\fR.
.TP
\fBTime Machine does not see backup share\fR
Verify \fBfruit time machine = yes\fR on the share and
\fBfruit extensions = yes\fR in \fB[global]\fR.
Check \fB_adisk._tcp\fR advertisement:
\fBavahi-browse \-rt _adisk._tcp\fR.
Verify TXT records contain \fBadVN=\fR and \fBadVU=\fR fields.
.TP
\fBSlow performance\fR
Enable leases: \fBsmb2 leases = yes\fR.
Enable oplocks on the share: \fBoplocks = yes\fR.
Increase I/O sizes: \fBsmb2 max read = 8M\fR, \fBsmb2 max write = 8M\fR.
For RDMA: increase \fBsmbd max io size\fR.
Check \fBmax worker threads\fR if authentication is a bottleneck.
.TP
\fBChanges not taking effect\fR
Share and user changes: \fBksmbdctl reload\fR is sufficient.
Global protocol/security changes: full restart required
(\fBksmbdctl stop && ksmbdctl start\fR).
.SH "ADMINISTRATION BEST PRACTICES"
.SS "Initial Setup"
.IP 1. 3
Load the kernel module: \fBmodprobe ksmbd\fR.
.IP 2. 3
Create users: \fBksmbdctl user add \fIusername\fR.
.IP 3. 3
Edit \fBksmbd.conf\fR or use \fBksmbdctl share add\fR.
.IP 4. 3
Set directory permissions on share paths.
.IP 5. 3
Start the daemon: \fBksmbdctl start\fR (or \fBsystemctl start ksmbd\fR).
.IP 6. 3
Verify: \fBksmbdctl status\fR and \fBksmbdctl features\fR.
.SS "Security Hardening"
.IP \(bu 3
Disable SMB1: Set \fBserver min protocol = SMB2_10\fR (or higher).
.IP \(bu 3
Require signing: Set \fBserver signing = mandatory\fR.
.IP \(bu 3
Require encryption: Set \fBsmb3 encryption = mandatory\fR (SMB3 clients only).
.IP \(bu 3
Restrict guest access: Set \fBmap to guest = never\fR and \fBguest ok = no\fR.
.IP \(bu 3
Use \fBhosts allow\fR and \fBhosts deny\fR with CIDR notation.
.IP \(bu 3
Protect the password database: \fBchmod 0600 ksmbdpwd.db\fR.
.IP \(bu 3
Use Kerberos instead of NTLM where possible.
.IP \(bu 3
Bind to specific interfaces: \fBbind interfaces only = yes\fR.
.IP \(bu 3
Set \fBrestrict anonymous = 1\fR or \fB2\fR to prevent anonymous enumeration.
.SS "Monitoring"
.IP \(bu 3
Check status: \fBksmbdctl status\fR.
.IP \(bu 3
Review features: \fBksmbdctl features\fR.
.IP \(bu 3
Watch kernel logs: \fBjournalctl \-kf \-u ksmbd\fR.
.IP \(bu 3
Check daemon logs: \fBjournalctl \-u ksmbd \-f\fR.
.IP \(bu 3
List active shares: \fBksmbdctl share list \-\-live\fR.
.SS "Backup and Restore"
The entire ksmbd configuration consists of two files:
.IP \(bu 3
\fB/usr/local/etc/ksmbd/ksmbd.conf\fR \(em share configuration.
.IP \(bu 3
\fB/usr/local/etc/ksmbd/ksmbdpwd.db\fR \(em user database (contains password hashes).
.PP
Back up both files regularly.
Restore by copying them back and running \fBksmbdctl reload\fR
(or restarting for global changes).
.SH FILES
.TP
\fB/usr/local/etc/ksmbd/ksmbd.conf\fR
Server configuration file (INI format). See \fBksmbd.conf\fR(5).
Contains the \fB[global]\fR section and per-share sections.
.TP
\fB/usr/local/etc/ksmbd/ksmbdpwd.db\fR
User password database. See \fBksmbdpwd.db\fR(5).
Plain text, one \fIuser\fR:\fIhash\fR per line.
Should be mode 0600, owned by root.
.TP
\fB/usr/local/etc/ksmbd/ksmbd.subauth\fR
Optional sub-authentication configuration.
.TP
\fB/usr/local/var/run/ksmbd.lock\fR
PID lock file for the daemon process.
Contains the daemon PID; used by \fBstop\fR and \fBreload\fR commands.
.TP
\fB/usr/local/var/run/ksmbd.fifo\fR
Named pipe used for share listing communication between the control
tool and the daemon.
Created dynamically when \fBshare list \-\-live\fR is invoked.
.TP
\fB/sys/class/ksmbd\-control/kill_server\fR
Sysfs attribute to shut down the ksmbd kernel server.
Writing \fB"hard"\fR terminates all connections immediately.
.TP
\fB/sys/class/ksmbd\-control/debug\fR
Sysfs attribute to toggle kernel debug components.
Reading it shows currently enabled components.
Writing a component name toggles it.
.TP
\fB/sys/module/ksmbd/version\fR
Sysfs attribute showing the ksmbd kernel module version string.
.SH "EXIT STATUS"
.TP
\fB0\fR
Operation completed successfully.
.TP
\fB1\fR
An error occurred (invalid arguments, missing files, permission
denied, daemon not running, module not loaded, etc.).
Error details are printed to stderr.
.SH EXAMPLES
.SS "Initial Server Setup"
.nf
# Load the kernel module
sudo modprobe ksmbd

# Create a user
ksmbdctl user add alice

# Create a share
ksmbdctl share add documents \\
    \-o "path = /srv/smb/documents" \\
    \-o "comment = Shared Documents" \\
    \-o "read only = no"

# Start the server
sudo ksmbdctl start

# Verify
ksmbdctl status
ksmbdctl features
.fi
.SS "Time Machine Setup"
.nf
# Add the share
ksmbdctl share add timemachine \\
    \-o "path = /srv/smb/timemachine" \\
    \-o "read only = no" \\
    \-o "fruit time machine = yes" \\
    \-o "fruit time machine max size = 500G" \\
    \-o "vfs objects = acl_xattr streams_xattr"

# Configure mDNS
sudo ksmbd\-mdns\-configure

# Reload
ksmbdctl reload
.fi
.SS "Debugging a Connection Issue"
.nf
# Check server is running
ksmbdctl status

# Enable protocol and auth tracing
ksmbdctl debug set smb
ksmbdctl debug set auth

# Watch kernel output
dmesg \-wH

# After debugging, disable
ksmbdctl debug off
.fi
.SS "Security Hardened Configuration"
.nf
# In ksmbd.conf [global]:
#   server min protocol = SMB3_00
#   server signing = mandatory
#   smb3 encryption = mandatory
#   map to guest = never
#   restrict anonymous = 2
#   bind interfaces only = yes
#   interfaces = eth0

# Restart to apply global changes
sudo ksmbdctl stop
sudo ksmbdctl start
.fi
.SS "Managing Shares"
.nf
# Add a public read-only share
ksmbdctl share add public \\
    \-o "path = /srv/smb/public" \\
    \-o "read only = yes" \\
    \-o "guest ok = yes"

# Update a share parameter
ksmbdctl share update public \-o "comment = Public Files"

# Show share configuration
ksmbdctl share show public

# List all shares
ksmbdctl share list

# Delete a share
ksmbdctl share delete public
.fi
.SS "User Management"
.nf
# Add user with inline password (scripts)
ksmbdctl user add bob \-p "s3cret"

# Update password interactively
ksmbdctl user update bob

# List all users
ksmbdctl user list

# Delete a user
ksmbdctl user delete bob
.fi
.SH "REMOVED LEGACY COMMANDS"
The legacy command names \fBksmbd.addshare\fR, \fBksmbd.adduser\fR,
\fBksmbd.control\fR, and \fBksmbd.mountd\fR are no longer installed.
Invoke \fBksmbdctl\fR directly.
.PP
Migration mapping:
.TS
l l.
Legacy Command	Equivalent
_
ksmbd.mountd	ksmbdctl start
ksmbd.control \-\-shutdown	ksmbdctl stop
ksmbd.control \-\-reload	ksmbdctl reload
ksmbd.control \-\-debug=COMP	ksmbdctl debug set COMP
ksmbd.control \-\-ksmbd\-version	ksmbdctl version
ksmbd.control \-\-list	ksmbdctl share list \-\-live
ksmbd.control \-\-status	ksmbdctl status
ksmbd.control \-\-features	ksmbdctl features
ksmbd.adduser USER	ksmbdctl user set USER
ksmbd.adduser \-a USER	ksmbdctl user add USER
ksmbd.adduser \-d USER	ksmbdctl user delete USER
ksmbd.adduser \-u USER	ksmbdctl user update USER
ksmbd.addshare SHARE	ksmbdctl share set SHARE
ksmbd.addshare \-a SHARE	ksmbdctl share add SHARE
ksmbd.addshare \-d SHARE	ksmbdctl share delete SHARE
ksmbd.addshare \-u SHARE	ksmbdctl share update SHARE
.TE
.SH SIGNALS
When running in daemon mode (\fBksmbdctl start\fR), the daemon responds to:
.TP
\fBSIGHUP\fR
Reload configuration files (\fBksmbd.conf\fR and \fBksmbdpwd.db\fR).
Sets the \fBKSMBD_SHOULD_RELOAD_CONFIG\fR flag internally.
.TP
\fBSIGUSR1\fR
Write share listing to the named pipe (\fBksmbd.fifo\fR).
Used internally by \fBksmbdctl share list \-\-live\fR.
Sets the \fBKSMBD_SHOULD_LIST_CONFIG\fR flag.
.TP
\fBSIGTERM\fR, \fBSIGINT\fR, \fBSIGQUIT\fR
Shut down gracefully.
The daemon sends a \fBSHUTTING_DOWN\fR event to the kernel
module and exits.
Clears the \fBKSMBD_HEALTH_RUNNING\fR flag.
